{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637086"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:37:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:37:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17628"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17628"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.19,0,0.78,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71811"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10342"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17628"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57300"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10041"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24247"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71811"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDietary lipids require special mechanisms for absorption in the gastrointestinal tract due to their hydrophobic nature. Most of this absorbtion occurs in the small bowel.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of lipid absorption?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Active transport via specific protein carriers","Direct diffusion through intestinal cell membranes","Facilitated diffusion through membrane channels","Formation of micelles that cross the aqueous boundary layer","Paracellular absorption between enterocytes"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of micelles that cross the aqueous boundary layer\u003C/strong\u003E is essential for lipid absorption. Micelles are formed when bile salts emulsify dietary lipids, creating small water-soluble aggregates that can traverse the aqueous environment adjacent to intestinal epithelial cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect diffusion through intestinal cell membranes\u003C/strong\u003E - Lipids are too large and hydrophobic to directly cross cell membranes without first being incorporated into micelles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport via specific protein carriers\u003C/strong\u003E - While some fatty acids may use protein carriers, this is not the primary mechanism for dietary lipid absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacellular absorption between enterocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - Lipids are too large to pass through tight junctions between cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitated diffusion through membrane channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Lipids do not use membrane channels for absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter crossing the aqueous boundary layer via micelles, individual lipid molecules can then diffuse into enterocytes. Inside the cells, long-chain fatty acids are re-esterified into triglycerides and packaged into chylomicrons for transport via lymphatics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dietary lipids are absorbed in the small intestine as micelles containing bile salts, fatty acids, and monoglycerides.","Micelles enable fat-soluble substances to cross the aqueous boundary layer to reach intestinal epithelial cells.","Long-chain fatty acids are re-esterified into triglycerides and packaged into chylomicrons for lymphatic transport."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57300"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17628"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57300"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T16:14:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T16:15:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10342"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71811"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","link